The former was for a long time believed to be the work of Aemilius Probus, a grammarian of the time ol Theodosius, on account of an epigram ol his which appears in the manuscripts after the life of Hannibal. ln this epigram Probus dedicates a work to Theodosius, which was assumed to be the collection of biographies which pre- ceded it. That view is now generally rejected and is altogether untenable‚ especially on stylistic grounds.

iii. His STYLE.

The style of Nepos is simple and pleasing. His vocabulary is limited‚ and he expresses himself as a rule in short sen- tences, When he occasionally attempts longer periodS, it is evident that he is not at home in them. He shows consider- able skill and taste in the order of his words. He is some- times careless, especially in the omission of pronounS, but as a rule is very clear.
